sec.p:
Both the new species are strongly associated with forest habitats (
Table 4 ). Cilliba cassideasimilis is widely dispersed in Europe (
), but its distribution is clearly disjunct. It has not been recorded so far from France , despite the existence of suitable habitats and climatic conditions there. It is also unknown from Great Britain , Belgium and the Netherlands , possibly due to extensive deforestation in those areas. In Poland , C. cassideasimilis is the most common and abundant species in the genus (
), occurring in fir­beech and beech forests in both mountains and lowlands (
A). Its optimum altitude is below 700 m a.s.l., but it has also been recorded in high mountains (
A). C. rafalskii occurs infrequently at sites distributed over all areas of Poland (
,
). It occupies forest habitats, preferring the litter of oak­hornbeam forests and other multispecies leafy forests (
B). The optimum altitude for this species is below 500 m a.s.l. (
B).
